---
description: Always load and apply repository cursorrules
alwaysApply: true
---

Before doing any work in this repository, read `@.cursorrules` and execute its
requirements.

## Why this rule exists

Cursor Agent, Background Agent, and other headless runtimes often **do not**
auto-load the legacy repository root `.cursorrules` file into the model context.
The `@.cursorrules` chat mention helps humans in the IDE but is **not** a
substitute for you reading the file when your session might omit it.

## Mandatory first step (every session)

Before your **first** repository tool call (search, read, terminal, edit, and so
on) in a session, read the **repository root** `.cursorrules` file in full using
your file-reading capability. If you already have the full current contents of
that file in context from this session, you do not need to re-read it until it
changes.

Minimum behavior for every task:

1. Load `.cursorrules` before analysis, planning, commands, or edits (see
   mandatory first step above).
2. Follow all mandatory and path-specific sections in that file.
3. Re-load `.cursorrules` if it is modified during the session.
4. Do not perform implementation actions until explicit user approval is
   provided for the current task.
5. Treat all write operations as implementation actions (file edits, dependency
   changes, migrations, generated artifacts, and `git add`/`git commit`/`git
   push`).

Do not continue with implementation if `.cursorrules` has not been applied.
